<title>E-Mail Senator Daschle -- SBSC</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<p>

You can use this form to send a letter to Minority Leader Daschle concerning the Immigration Reform Act. A letter has already been prepared for you, but please customize it to fit your needs. Remember to sign the letter!<p>

Here is Senator Daschle's email address if you want to send additional comments:
<a href="mailto:tom_daschle@daschle.senate.gov">tom_daschle@daschle.senate.gov</a>

<p>
<form action="/townhall/scripts/sbsc-email.cgi" method="post">
Your email address:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="a-email">
<p>
The subject of your email:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="b-subj" value="Immigration Reform Act">
<p>
Your message:<br>
<textarea cols="60" rows="10" wrap="physical" name="c-text">
Dear Senator: 

I urge you to terminate Senator Alan Simpson's (R. WY) legal 
immigration proposal, S. 1394, at the Senate subcommittee 
level. 

The Senate immigration subcommittee will soon begin markup 
of S. 1394. Unfortunately, Senator Simpson's legal 
immigration legislation intensifies the restrictive measures
of Representative Lamar Smith's (R. TX) immigration 
proposal, H.R. 2202. 

Senator Simpson seeks a 25% tax on businesses that hire 
foreign workers. Under S. 1394, companies hiring foreign 
help would have to pay a tax equal to one-quarter of 
the employee's annual compensation including wages and 
benefits. In addition, employers would be forced to pay 
that employee 105% of the prevailing wage (an expansion of 
the job-killing Davis-Bacon Act). 

Additionally, the new limits on skilled immigration coupled 
with the arbitrary experience requirements will 
significantly lower the number of skilled workers admitted 
to the U.S. annually. Moreover, elimination of the unskilled
immigration visas, prevents families from uniting. Unskilled
immigrants do not displace American workers. The measures of
S. 1394 (and similary House proposals) will do more to 
displace American workers than any perceived move by 
employers to bypass American labor for foreign workers. 

Contrary to the less government principles espoused in 1994,
S. 1394 and similar House proposals, increase government 
spending, expand governmental control over businesses and 
will ultimately weaken the U.S. economy. I strongly oppose 
S. 1394, and I ask you to do the same. 

Sincerely,
</textarea>
